sub_title: Supporting the pharma and biotechnology industries to develop new medications and treatments through clinical studies. Building a safer, cleaner and healthier world.
summary:
Experienced Client Services Project Manager helping the pharmaceutical industry and clinical research organisations to succeed in their clinical studies to development new medications and treatments. 

Alongside, constantly building up business relationships within my client’s portfolio to build a planet safer, cleaner and healthier.

Proud to be part of Thermo Fisher Scientific, world leader in serving science. Our mission is to enable our customers to make the world healthier, cleaner and safer.

awards:
[{'title': "Master Thesis 'How lean production can intrinsically motivate production-line employees in Austria, Croatia and Slovenia'", 'description': 'Recent studies and the positive outcome of intrinsic motivation brought the author to research deeper
on the topic and to give a useful application for manufacturing companies. The configuration of lean-production jobs seems to be repetitive and complicated to reach intrinsic motivation for production-line
employees. Some studies targeted already the same purpose, but they lack contextual foundation
and empirical evidence.
This research aims to figure out how lean-production job design can intrinsically motivate
production-line employees in countries like Austria, Croatia, and Slovenia. The study offers a model
to reach such purpose that has been theoretically and empirically tested. Therefore, this master thesis
involves a review of relevant literature in the field of intrinsic motivation and motivational theories,
cross-cultural differences that moderate the main dimensions of intrinsic motivation as well as
generally define primary cultural characteristics of Austria, Croatia, and Slovenia to bring the
internationality to the purpose of the research. Moreover, literature and studies in the field of leanproduction are consequently revised.
Following the literature review, it is identified four major dimensions that contribute to enhance
intrinsic motivation. As said above, culture moderates its application depending on the country. The
analysis of the qualitative research through semi-structure interviews together with the report of
Great Place to Work, it offers a test of what it is found out in the literature review and an answer of
the main research question.
Both types of research, theoretical and empirical, contribute to assert that lean-production job design
can intrinsically motivate production-line employees and its elements to reach it. Thus, a theoretical
and empirically tested model is generated in order to provide a useful tool for companies that operate
in the same industry or similar in countries like Austria, Croatia, and Slovenia. ', 'issuer': None, 'date': {'month': 7, 'day': None, 'year': 2017}}]
